        "text": "Rustam SHUKUROV\n\nFOREIGNERS IN THE EMPIRE OF TREBIZOND (THE CASE OF ORIENTALS AND LATINS)\n\nThe history of the Empire of Trebizond represents a remarkable phenomenon. On the one hand, the Empire of Trebizond was socially and culturally an integral part of the Byzantine Hellenistic world. Culturally and ideologically, the point of attraction for the Byzantine Pontos lay in Constantinople and the Byzantine Balkans. The Pontic Greeks travelled to the Byzantine West in search of a better education or better life, like the Cardinal Bessarion, the father of the Eugenikoi brothers, and George of Trebizond's parents, or those among the Pontic aristocrats who went to Palaiologan Byzantium between the thirteenth and fifteenth centuries. From those who emigrated, Trebizond gained (albeit rather sporadically) new intellectual and spiritual force from the Byzantine West, and they were often awarded prominent positions in the Empire. Among the emigrants thus favored were Gregory Chioniades, a physician, astronomer and ecclesiastic from Constantinople, who visited Trebizond many times, spent his last years there and died in the Empire (ca. 1330); Constantine Loukites (d. 1340), born in Macedonia and educated in Constantinople, was protonotarios and protovestiarios of the Empire; Andrew Libadenos (d. after 1361), a Constantinopolitan, was a famously sophisticated writer and chartophylakos of the Trapezuntine Metropolitan. The Trapezuntine Metropolis and monas¬ teries also benifited from the influx of ecclesiastics from Byzantine West and Athonite monks.1 Were these emigrants foreigners to the Trapezuntines? Yes and no. Yes, because the Empire of Trebizond was not politically a part of the Palaiologian State of the \"Romans\" and was often regarded by supercilious Western Byzantines as the barbaric land of \"Lazs\"; no, because Western Byzantines acknowledged that linguistically and culturally the Empire was a part of the Byzantine world.\n\nOn the other hand, a geographical quirk firmly isolated the Pontic Byzantines in a remote Anatolian region, a hundred miles away from the centres of Byzantine culture in the West. In the fourteenth century, Trebizond was separated from Constantinople by as many as 10 to 20 days of the fastest sea voyage. A route over land between Constantinople and Trebizond theoretically existed but, being slow, tiresome and dangerous, was no longer in use. Rather, the European power closest to Trebizond was the Italian city states: the Black Sea linked Trebizond with the Genoese and Venetian colonies in the Crimea and North Anatolia. The Italians thus played an increasingly central role in the economic and political life of the Empire until its conquest by the Ottomans in 1461."
